prompt:
The escape-room prop controller needs a maze module and the vendor one is a black box, so I'm having it rebuilt in plain C: generation with Kruskal over a union-find, a right-hand wall-follower to verify solvability, ASCII rendering for the debug console. Everything must be reproducible from a seed — the props are burned in pairs and both must carve the identical maze. Files: mazeuf.h and mazeuf.c, C17, stdint/stddef/string only, no I/O, no heap.

    typedef struct { int16_t parent[256]; int16_t size[256]; int n; } uf;

    int uf_init(uf *u, int n);
    int uf_find(uf *u, int x);
    int uf_union(uf *u, int a, int b);

    #define MAZE_MAX 16
    typedef struct {
        int w, h;
        uint8_t open_e[MAZE_MAX][MAZE_MAX];   /* open_e[r][c]: passage (r,c)->(r,c+1) */
        uint8_t open_s[MAZE_MAX][MAZE_MAX];   /* open_s[r][c]: passage (r,c)->(r+1,c) */
    } maze;

    int maze_generate(maze *m, int w, int h, uint32_t seed);
    int maze_render(const maze *m, char *buf, size_t cap);
    int maze_solve(const maze *m, char *dirs, size_t cap);

Union-find: uf_init sets n singletons (-1 if n outside 1..256, else 0). uf_find returns the current representative of x, -1 out of range. uf_union returns 1 when it merged two different sets, 0 when already together, -1 on bad input. Internals (path compression, by-size vs by-rank) are your call — the tests only ever compare find results for equality.

Generation, and this part is byte-exact so read twice:

1. Cells are (row, col), id = row*w + col. Build the wall list in EXACTLY this order: scan cells row-major (row 0 first, then within a row col 0 first); for each cell append its EAST wall (if col+1 < w) and then its SOUTH wall (if row+1 < h).
2. Shuffle that list with a Fisher-Yates driven by our house PRNG: state = (state * 1103515245 + 12345) mod 2^31, draw = state >> 16. Starting from state = seed: for i from len-1 down to 1, swap list[i] with list[draw % (i+1)].
3. Kruskal over the shuffled list in order: knock the wall down (set the matching open_e/open_s flag) exactly when union-find says the two cells are in different sets. A finished maze is a spanning tree: w*h-1 open passages, every cell reachable.

maze_generate validates w and h in [2,16] (-1, untouched otherwise; NULL too), zeroes both flag arrays, runs the above, returns 0.

maze_render draws (2h+1) lines of (2w+1) characters, each line '\n'-terminated, NUL at the end: cell interiors are spaces at odd-odd coordinates, everything else is '#' except that an open wall between two cells becomes a space between them. Border stays closed. If cap can't hold (2h+1)*(2w+2)+1 bytes, return -1 and leave the buffer alone; else return the character count (NUL excluded).

maze_solve runs the right-hand wall-follower from cell (0,0) to cell (h-1,w-1) and writes one letter per step into dirs ('N','E','S','W', NUL-terminated): start FACING EAST; each step try, in order, the direction to your RIGHT (clockwise: N->E->S->W->N), then STRAIGHT, then LEFT, then BACK, and take the first one with an open passage; a step both moves and becomes the new facing. Yes, the follower walks into dead ends and back out — that's what I want to see on the console, the raw wall-hugging trace, not a cleaned-up path. Stop the moment you stand on the exit cell. Return the step count, or -1 if dirs can't hold the trace plus NUL.

make test is the gate; the suite pins exact renders and exact follower traces per seed. Makefile, mintest.h, test_mazeuf.c are fixed.
